He stated that a multipurpose sculpture will eventually be installed in the island, with the cooperation of the Egyptian Plastic Arts Centre. “At the moment, I cannot give details regarding the theme behind the project,” Szabo said.

The Italian sculptor started his journey in art when he was only a boy after he inherited bronze statues from his grandfather, back in his home town Şoreşt, Transilvania, and studying under masters, such as Albertino Tubeman.

Before coming to Egypt, Szabó lived and worked in several cities including Transilvania, the UK, and Venice. Over his long experience, he has met and collaborated with significant names in the field, such as sculptors Jorge Perez De Lara, Justin Marozzi, Andrea Francolini, Flavia Acciardi, Gugliermo Bardi, Luca Antonio Bazzani, Alberto Mariga Cicati and Adele Carpena.

At the moment he’s trying to adopt a new research path with visual thinkers such as Chinese filmmakers Chen Shi-Zheng and Rose Barosi, Chinese musician and painter Feng Shengyin, mixed-media conceptualist Ellen Zweig and American cinematographer Ken Malbit. He is also working on a new performance/film project to construct with poet Ondrej Hanák and producer Sean Spencer in his short free-time.
